  "opinion": "As a woman in my late forties who works as a cleaner in Los Angeles and grew up in a household where one parent had a master’s degree and the other only a primary school education, I’ve seen firsthand how the gender gap in science affects real people. The gap isn’t just about fewer women in labs or classrooms—it’s about the invisible barriers that make it hard for women like me to even think about pursuing science. My parents’ different educational backgrounds taught me early that opportunities aren’t always equal, and that’s something I’ve carried with me. I’m anxious about the future, especially when I see how little attention is given to women in STEM fields, even when they’re working hard in roles that require critical thinking. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. For instance, my local community center offers workshops on science basics for women with vocational training, and it’s helped some of my neighbors feel more confident. We need programs that don’t assume people have the same starting point, like my own background. It’s not just about fixing the system—it’s about creating spaces where women feel safe to ask questions without judgment. And how? By listening to women who’ve already made it, like the scientists I’ve met through my photography hobby who share their experiences. The gap is real, but it’s also fixable if we start with empathy and practical steps, not just big speeches. I believe in change, but it has to be slow and thoughtful, especially for those of us who’ve had to navigate life with less support.",
